node.text:
On this episode of AD Visits, sartorial sensation Eva Chen (@evachen212) invites us inside her Connecticut home designed by local firm @hendrickschurchill. See her many reading nooks, her @instagram-worthy kitchen, and more. Cover photo by @chrismottalini; styled by Dorcia Kelly.

Visit our link in bio to read more about her home.

node.text:
One of the most exciting aspects of design is that it changes constantly. The points of view found in the shapes, colors, and styles of our favorite spaces are ever evolving, as are the voices that bring those spaces to life. Coast to coast, a fresh crop of creative talents is writing the next chapter in great interior design—and they're names you need to know.

Meet them at our bio link. Produced by @alevasseur1; photos by (in order of appearance) @denver_photo, @simbarashecha, @phyliciajphotography, @samfroststudio, @laurencrew, @meghanmarin, @jet1220, and @phyliciajphotography; caption by @e.portale; words by @_h_mart_, @madeleineluckel, @sopherring, @samuelcochran, and @mayer.rus.

node.text:
Architects delight in constraints. A sheer cliff, an enormous boulder, some mature trees—every challenge is an opportunity, every obstacle a eureka moment. Enlisted by a creative couple to update their Manhattan town house, #AD100 talent Giancarlo Valle (@studiogiancarlovalle) found no such conditions to navigate. Recently constructed and lacking in character, the five-story downtown dwelling was just box rooms, white walls, and soulless developer details—an aesthetic vacuum, for all intents and purposes. And so, deprived of any natural jumping-off points, Valle created his own. “A project like this, it’s a blank canvas,” he reflects. “You almost have to create the game.”

Tour the brilliant home he designed at our bio link. Photo by @stephenkentjohnson; styling by @colinking; design by @studiogiancarlovalle; words by @samuelcochran.

node.text:
Architecturally speaking, the landmark Wilshire Boulevard Temple (@wilshireboulevardtemple), home to the oldest Jewish congregation in Los Angeles, is a tough act to follow. Built in 1929 and designed by architect Abram M. Edelman in a hybrid of Byzantine and Romanesque styles, the magnificent domed synagogue has all the exotic glamour of the great movie palaces of the era. OMA (@oma.eu @omanewyork), the Rotterdam-based Office for Metropolitan Architecture, won the WBT commission for a new structure, the Audrey Irmas Pavilion, on the congregation’s Erika J. Glazer Family Campus.

Step inside the new pavilion at our bio link. Photo by @jasonorear; design by @shohei_shigematsu; words by @mayer.rus.

node.text:
Somewhere on the Floridian coast, one sophisticated Palm Beach residence possesses a particularly compelling mise-en-scène: A 6,000-square-foot waterfront location, paired with a façade that recalls an uber chic super yacht on terra firma. The international-style pied-à-terre—conceptualized and brought to life by architect and interior designer Gerard Beekman of Gramatan Architecture and Design and @livingstonbuilders_inc—serves as a much-needed winter reprieve for a Chicago-based couple and their twin daughters, who jaunt down on weekends from New York City.

See the yacht-inspired home at our bio link. Photo by @sargentphotos; design by Gerard Beekman and @livingstonbuilders_inc; words by @katiekiefner.

node.text:
Designer @brigetteromanek has translated her philosophy of livable luxury into a bright, breezy line of home furnishings for retailer Mitchell Gold + Bob Williams (@mgbwhome). “I like furniture that’s practical—the right pitch, the right level of comfort—but there has to be more. There has to be an element of playfulness and joy,” says the #AD100 designer, whose LA collection blends rounded silhouettes and taut forms for a distinctly upbeat personality, more timeless than trendy.

Get an exclusive first look at her collection at our bio link. Photo by @williamwaldronphoto; design by @brigetteromanek; words by @mayer.rus.

node.text:
"What makes projects special are the people living in them—but Tish and Tom are on a whole other level.” So says @rachelchudley, a British interior decorator known for funky-chic rooms that are full of surprises. The name-checked clients would be Londoners @tishweinstock, a @vogue writer and beauty editor, and @tom_guinness, a model turned soulful fashion stylist. “Both have style with an edge,” Chudley continues, adding that the finished product, a house for the couple and their toddler son, Reuben, “walks the line between old and new and bad taste and good taste.”

Tour their London townhouse at our bio link. Photo by @simonuptonphotos; styling by @saramathersstylist; design by @rachelchudley; words by @mrmitchowens.

node.text:
@willoperron’s design for the L.A. offices of the entertainment behemoth @rocnation, Jay-Z's entertainment company, has little to do with razzle-dazzle. “I didn’t want it to feel like a caricatured media or management office, with music blaring and video screens everywhere. I wasn’t interested in that kind of sensory over-​load,” Perron explains. “I wanted to do the opposite, to create a zen environment conducive to ideas and conversation, a space where you can actually think,” he adds.

Tour Roc Nation's sophisticated offices at our bio link. Photo by @shadedeggesphotography; styling by @emilyedithbowser; design by @willoperron; words by @mayer.rus.

Mark your calendars: The Iconic Home returns this month. In partnership with @blackinteriordesignersnetwork, the entirely virtual home will showcase the work of 12 Black interior designers and architects, as well as the work of Black artists. Join us as we learn about living stylishly and sustainably while touring the imaginative spaces of this year's roster of names.

Visit the link in our bio to stay up to date on all updates leading up to the event.

node.text:
#AD100 designer @indiamahdavi developed a traveler’s eye for place before she was a teenager, filing away mental images as she moved from her father’s homeland of Iran to the U.S., then Germany, and finally France with her parents and siblings. Settling into a family apartment in the French Riviera, she would wake up to dappled sunshine on green grass, white shutters against ochre walls, and the ultra-marine haze of the sea a few miles away.

See her work her magic on a friend's home at our bio link. Photo by Vincent Leroux; design by @indiamahdavi; words by @samedford.

node.text:
The owner of this Mexican home and his #AD100 designer have a long history of working together: @luislaplace designed the executive’s apartments in Paris and New York City in addition to a handsome 18th-century building he owns in the colonial town of Morelia, Mexico, which Laplace converted into a café/bookshop/pied-à-terre. “I like Luis’s sense of aesthetics and the way he blends beautiful furniture and textiles with local materials and crafts,” the executive says now. “We have similar visions.”

Explore our cover home at our bio link. Photo by @fernandomarroquint; styling by Mariana Estrada; design by @luislaplace; words by @danathomasparis.

node.text:
A passionate cinephile, the Mexican movie executive knows the impact a dramatic setting can have on the senses. So when he heard that a sprawling villa perched on a bluff overlooking the Pacific Ocean in Mexico was for sale, he snapped it up. Then he called the Paris-based Argentinean #AD100 architect @luislaplace to create a family and business retreat that would be theatrical as well as welcoming.

Step inside the stunning home gracing our October cover at our bio link. Photo by @fernandomarroquint; styling by Mariana Estrada; design by @luislaplace; words by @danathomasparis.

node.text:
In this secluded Malibu home, designer Vanessa Alexander (@alexanderdesignbuild) turned an awkward space into a funky movie-night room with a big daybed pushed into a corner. It’s made cozier thanks to velvet-covered walls. Turning this space into a guest room is also possible thanks to the full-height velvet curtains. A @toddhido_ photograph adds mood and mystery.

Step inside the beautiful spaces at our bio link. Photo by @douglasfriedman; styling by @rowelosangeles; design by @alexanderdesignbuild; words by @leilanimarielabong.
